{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17563397","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17563397"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T22:58:01+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T22:58:01+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16754"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16754","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16754"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.5,0.08,0.25,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9445"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"89971"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9445","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9445"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16754"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74130"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"27"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"3496"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4976"},{"type":"tags","id":"8995"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11635"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22325"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30648"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"89971","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/89971"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 24-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a three-day history of an intensely itchy, red rash on both hands. She started working as a hairdresser two weeks ago. She has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. She has never experienced similar symptoms before.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There are erythematous, scaly patches with small vesicles on the dorsal aspects of both hands and between her fingers. The palms are relatively spared.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Change of occupation","Patch testing","Topical antibiotics","Regular moisturiser only","Oral antihistamines alone"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis presentation is typical of allergic contact dermatitis in a hairdresser, likely due to exposure to chemicals such as hair dyes, bleaches, or preservatives. The distribution on the hands, timing of onset after starting work, and morphology of the rash are characteristic.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPatch testing\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next step to identify the specific substance causing the allergy. Small amounts of common allergens are applied to the back using special patches. These are left in place for 48 hours, then removed to check for any skin reactions. A final check is done after 96 hours. Once the specific allergen is identified, appropriate protective measures can be implemented.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChange of occupation\u003C/strong\u003E is too drastic as an initial step. Many hairdressers can continue their profession successfully with proper identification of allergens and implementation of preventive measures such as appropriate glove use.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral antihistamines alone\u003C/strong\u003E may help with symptoms but do not address the underlying cause. Without identifying and avoiding the causative allergen, the condition will likely persist or recur.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETopical antibiotics\u003C/strong\u003E are not indicated as this is not an infectious condition. The vesicular appearance is characteristic of allergic contact dermatitis rather than infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERegular moisturiser only\u003C/strong\u003E would be insufficient treatment. While moisturisers are important in skin care, they will not prevent reactions to allergens, and the condition will likely worsen without proper identification and avoidance of the triggering substance.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe management of occupational contact dermatitis involves a comprehensive approach including allergen identification, appropriate protective measures, and skin care education. Secondary prevention strategies such as proper glove selection and use, regular hand care, and workplace modifications are essential for long-term management.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Allergic contact dermatitis typically develops 24-48 hours after exposure to the allergen and persists until the allergen is removed.","A detailed occupational history is essential in diagnosing work-related contact dermatitis.","Management of occupational contact dermatitis involves allergen identification and avoidance, along with appropriate skin protection measures.","Patch testing is a simple diagnostic test where potential allergens are applied to the skin and reactions are assessed after 48-96 hours."],"references":["Hougaard MG, Menn\u00e9 T, S\u00f8sted H. Occupational eczema and asthma in a hairdresser caused by hair-bleaching products. Dermatitis. 2012;23(6):284-7. doi:10.1097/DER.0b013e318275968c.","Diepgen TL. Occupational skin diseases. J Dtsch Dermatol Ges. 2012;10(5):297\u2013315. doi:10.1111/j.1610-0387.2012.07890.x","Occupational skin disease | DermNet [Internet]. Dermnetnz.org. 2022. Available at: https://dermnetnz.org/topics/occupational-skin-disease\u200c","Coulson, I. Patch tests. DermNet. Updated Dec 2021. [cited 2025 Mar 11]. Available at: https://dermnetnz.org/topics/patch-testsPatch tests"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74130"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16754"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74130","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/74130"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-11T14:54:53+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-03-11T14:54:53+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9445"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"89971"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"27","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/27"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc77","name":"Occupational/Environmental Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group